Species Comments: A very large flock of hundreds of Snow Geese near the highway. Stopped and looked at them from a distance; I'm not proficient at judging numbers like this, but there were at least 1000.

Saw Ross's Geese gliding amongst the Canada Geese. Round head, completely white except for black tail feathers, and small - suspected Snow Goose initially, but they didn't fit with the ones I'd seen before in Vermont and Quebec. The bill was grey from my vantage point, but I was quite far away. Debated this a lot, here, and after, and decided on a Ross identification for a few reason: the bill was small and triangular, and not large enough for a Snow; there was a lack of the huge grin on a Snow Goose; and the birds themselves were noticeably smaller than the Canada Geese. The all-white head lacked any rust-color I'd expect to see in a Snow Goose, too.

Species Comments: Flying from the south east, with strong wing beats. When it soared, it had a slight bent to the wings, in a dihedral. This, combined with the knowledge that there has been a Golden Eagle in the area, confirmed to me that it was not a Bald Eagle. Size eliminated anything else. It soared low behind the cow sheds southeast of the yellow barn. I and some others weren't able to find it again; I was the only one to spot it in a party of four. Seen from halfway past Field 40 towards the barn, well down from the usual wishing well spot.

Continuing bird. Flew north across road and alighted in a tree on the other side of the field, over turkeys, which didn't seem upset. We were a good ways off, so this might be a shy bird.    The eagle was all dark, and its size ruled out a rare dark morph Red-Tailed Hawk. On the upper side of the wings were golden patches, and it lacked white spots underneath which would have indicated an immature Bald Eagle. Head was buffy. When it glided (briefly), it was clearly with a dihedral slant to the wings, as opposed to the Bald's flat flight. The tail was surprisingly narrow from my viewpoint.

Species Comments: This was a difficult bird to ID. While standing outside of the Adamant Community Art Center, I heard a low waaah call, very similar to a gull. Looking towards the church down the road, I saw a large, gull-sized bird with white underwings curl over and land on a branch. I took off running and got close enough to see it was a bulky accipiter species. It was too small to be a Red-tailed Hawk, the other main hawk in the area. However, the light was not good, and its tail seemed shorter than I expected for an accipiter. The temperature was roughly 4°F, and I now think that it was intentionally fluffing its feathers and staying compact in order to stay warm. When it took off, it lacked the normal accipiter quick wing bears, and seemed to have more rounded wing tips. The white underside was still evident, with a dark back. Having listened to calls online, and considering the initial white flash, the size of the bird (too large to be a Cooper, definitely not a Sharpie), the slow wing beats, the rounded wing shape, I'm fairly confident this was a Goshawk. However, I don't know why it gave a 'waah' call, as those are traditionally near a nest. I can't explain it.

Species Comments: Initially identified as Bohemian's, as I saw them down the road earlier. However, another eBirder identified them as Cedar's. Looking at Sibley again, I see that Bohemian's have red undertail coverts, while Cedars have white. I remember thinking the birds seem whiter than usual when flying up, but I didn't have my book on me at the time. I now think this may have been due to white undertail coverts, with matching lack of black primaries. Changing to match the earlier reported Cedar accordingly.
